ianism to explain why he remains such a touchstone for understanding Canadian foreign policy. Leading and emerging scholars dig deeply into Pearson’s diplomatic and political career, especially during the 1960s and his time as prime minister. Topics range from peacekeeping and Arctic sovereignty to environmental diplomacy and human rights policy. They show that competing forces of idealism and pragmatism were key drivers of Pearsonian foreign policy and how global events often influenced politics and society within Canada itself. Situating Pearson within his times and as a lens through which to analyze Canadians’ views of global affairs, this nuanced collection wrestles with the contradictions of Pearson and Pearsonianism and, ultimately, with the resulting myths surrounding Canada’s role in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrime ministerszCanadavBiography. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAzzi, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBothwell, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Michael K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapnick, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirks, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaghy, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnglish, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillmer, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKikkert, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel